revision.text:
Many '''[[international organizations]]''' also have '''[[Supranationalism|supranational]] aspects''', meaning that decisions can be made by the organization as a whole that are binding on member states that disagree.
==Definition of Supranationality Used== ''Political Unification Revisited: On Building Supranational Communities'' by Amitai Etzioni <ref>{{cite book | last = Etzioni | first =Amitai | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Political Unification Revisited: On Building Supranational Communities | publisher =Lexington Books | year = 2001 | location = Lanham | url = | doi = | id = | nopp = true | page = xix }}</ref> offers the definition of '''supranationality''' that is used in this entry. Etzioni writes that supranationality can be thought of as "a composite of several elements." These elements can be present alone or all together. The three elements of supranationality are defined as follows:
#Making of significant decisions by a body that is not made of national representatives and that does not receive instructions from national governments. (Though such a body is frequently elected by national authorities or their constituents. Frequently such a body is made up of officials acting in an individual capacity.) #The subjects or participants (national governments or individuals) are legally obligated to comply with the decisions of the body. #Individuals or other private parties may interact directly with the body and/or have legal obligations as stated above.
==Examples of Supranational Elements== {| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | '''[[European Court of Human Rights]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1950, Reformed 1998'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |Judges of the Court serve in an individual capacity. Though elected by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe, they receive no instructions from States or any entity outside the court and cannot be dismissed but by a vote of two thirds of their own grouping.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms | work =European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, Articles 22,24 | publisher = | date = | url = http://conventions.coe.int/treaty/en/Treaties/Html/005.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 1 |- |The Court can rule against the government of the offending States Parties. Judgements of the Court as to remedies for rights violations are binding on States Parties.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms | work = European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, Article 46 | publisher = | date = | url = http://conventions.coe.int/treaty/en/Treaties/Html/005.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The jurisdiction of the Court is automatically compulsory. The statute of the Court is a part of the European Convention on Human Rights and thus states party to the Convention are party to the Court. While not having initial jurisdiction over complaints, there is no provision for refusal by States brought before the Court.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms | work = | publisher = | date = | url = http://conventions.coe.int/treaty/en/Treaties/Html/005.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |Citizens of States Parties to the European Convention on Human Rights may bring their human rights grievances directly to an international body of judges (the Court), albeit only when all domestic remedies have been exhausted.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms | work = European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, Articles 34, 35 | publisher = | date = | url = http://conventions.coe.int/treaty/en/Treaties/Html/005.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 3 |}
{| class="wikitable" |- |style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | '''[[Inter-American Court of Human Rights]]''' |style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1979'' |- |style="background:lightgrey" |'''Aspect''' |style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |The Court can rule against the government of a State Party it finds has violated the [[American Convention on Human Rights]]. Judgements of the Court as to remedies for rights violations are binding on States Parties.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =American Convention on Human Rights | work = American Convention on Human Rights, Article 63, Paragraph 1 | publisher = | date = | url =http://www.oas.org/juridico/english/Treaties/b-32.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =American Convention on Human Rights | work = American Convention on Human Rights, Article 68, Paragraph 2 | publisher = | date = | url =http://www.oas.org/juridico/english/Treaties/b-32.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |States may accept compulsory jurisdiction of contentious cases through declaration. This means any other State Party accepting compulsory jurisdiction may bring a case against it before the Court. Alternatively the state declaring compulsory jurisdiction may be brought before the court by the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights over a complaint filed by an individual to the Commission.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =American Convention on Human Rights | work = American Convention on Human Rights, Article 62, Paragraph 1 | publisher = | date = | url =http://www.oas.org/juridico/english/Treaties/b-32.htm | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |Colspan = "2" |''Note: Unlike the European Court of Human Rights, there is no provision for direct application by individuals to the Court. Rather individuals must file a complaint with the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights, which may decide after exhausting non-contentious measures of resolution, to submit the complaint to the Court, on the condition the State Party to the Convention has accepted the jurisdiction of the Court.'' |}
{| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | '''[[International Court of Justice]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1922, Reformed 1945'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |The judges which compose the Court serve in a personal capacity, and though they are elected by the General Assembly on the advice of the Security Council, they are forbidden from receiving instructions from national governments or any entity outside the Court.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Statute of the International Court of Justice | work = Statute of the International Court of Justice, Article 4 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061002111840/http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-02}}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 1 |- | ICJ rulings in contentious cases are binding on the States Parties to the dispute. Thus its decisions have the status of a treaty obligation for the State Party in question.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Article 94, Paragraph 1 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04}}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |In case of non-compliance with decisions, the ICJ may refer a state party to the Security Council for enforcement, although this provision has never been used.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Article 94, Paragraph 2 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04 }}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The ICJ Statute is a self-executing treaty, meaning (dependent on the Constitutional provisions of the State Party in question) the provisions of the treaty are enforceable in the respective legal structures of States Parties, indistinguishable from national laws of the State Party. Taken with fact that decisions its decisions are indistinguishable in obligation from the Statute of the ICJ itself, the decisions of the ICJ have the status of national law in national courts.<ref>{{cite web | last = Ku | first = Julian | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =The Delegation of Federal Power to International Organizations: New Problems with Old Solutions | work = The Delegation of Federal Power to International Organizations: New Problems with Old Solutions | publisher = Minnesota Law Review, Vol 85:71 | year = 2000 | url =http://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/law_ku_delegation_federal.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Court has the power in a contentious case to indicate any provisional measures for the preservation of the rights of either party.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Statute of the International Court of Justice | work = Statute of the International Court of Justice, Article 41 | publisher = | date = | url =http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061002111840/http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-02}}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |States parties to the ICJ Statute may declare acceptance of the jurisdiction of the Court in all cases. This means that any other state party having declared compulsory jurisdiction as well may bring the state party before the Court for an alleged violation of international law. Should the ICJ decide to take up the dispute, the party is required to defend itself in a case before the ICJ and accept the decision of the Court. Certain treaties also confer on the ICJ compulsory jurisdiction over the treaty.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Statute of the International Court of Justice | work = Statute of the International Court of Justice, Article 36, Paragraph 2 | publisher = | date = | url =http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061002111840/http://www.icj-cij.org/icjwww/ibasicdocuments/ibasictext/ibasicstatute.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-02}}</ref> | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |}
{| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | '''[[International Criminal Court]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 2002'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |The Prosecutor may independently open investigations into cases of widespread violation of the Statute, such as war crimes, genocide, and crimes against Humanity, given the consent of the Pre-Trial Chamber. The Prosecutor may conduct investigations on the territory of a State Party.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Articles 53, 54 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 1 |- |Judges and members of the Office of the Prosecutor serve in a personal capacity and, though accountable to the Assembly of States Parties, act entirely independently and without instruction from national governments or any entity outside the Court.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 36 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 40 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 42 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 1 |- |The Court has jurisdiction over persons, who are individually responsible and punishable for crimes under the Statute, such as war crimes, genocide, and crimes against humanity.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 25 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2, 3 |- |The Pre-Trial Chamber may, after an investigation by the Prosecutor and on the application of the Prosecutor, issue a warrant of arrest for an individual if it has reasonable grounds to believe the individual has committed a crime under the Statute involved in the case under investigation by the Prosecutor.<ref name="icc-cpi.int">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 58 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2, 3 |- |Arrest warrants are binding on States Parties, which are obligated to take steps to arrest the person in question immediately.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 59 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Prosecutor of the Court, with the consent of the Pre-Trial Chamber, consisting of three judges, is authorized to directly summon a person if there are reasonable grounds to believe the person committed an alleged crime under the Statute and a summons is sufficient to ensure the person’s appearance.<ref name="icc-cpi.int"/> |align="center" width="120px" | 3 |- |Individuals concerned have the right to challenge an arrest warrant at the international level and apply at the international level for release pending trial.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 60 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 3 |}
