{| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | [[Image:Flag of the United Nations.svg|300x45px]]'''[[Security Council]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1945'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |The members of the United Nations agree that in carrying out its duties in maintaining peace and security, the Security Council Acts on their behalf.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter V, Article 24 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The members of the United Nations agree to accept and carry out the decisions of the Security Council. Thus Security Council resolutions are binding on involved member states, or even on all member states.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter V, Article 25 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Security Council may compel the members states to apply measures decided upon to give effect to its decisions, such as diplomatic or economic sanctions.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter VII, Article 41 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Security Council may take action through the use of military force to enforce its decisions and maintain or restore international peace and security. This provision has been used somewhat infrequently – the [[Korean War]] (1950), intervention in the [[Congo Crisis]](1961), the First Gulf Conflict (1991) <ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter VII, Article 42 | publisher = | year = 1945 | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Security Council may enforce the decisions of the International Court of Justice, although this provision has never been used.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter XIV, Article 94, Paragraph 1 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |The Security Council may create subsidiary organs to assist in carrying out its functions. Since the decisions of the Security Council are binding, the effect is that such subsidiary organs can add new ways for the Council to exercise its obligations. The most prominent examples of this were the creation of the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia and the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations Charter | work = [[United Nations Charter]], Chapter VI, Article 29 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.un.org/aboutun/charter | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 3 |- |The Statute of the International Criminal Court confers upon the Security Council an ability to refer situations of war crimes, crimes against humanity, or genocide in states not party to the Statute to the ICC for investigation and prosecution.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court | work = [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court]], Article 13 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.icc-cpi.int/library/about/officialjournal/Rome_Statute_120704-EN.pdf | format = | doi = | accessdate = }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 3 |}
{| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | [[Image:Flag of the United Nations.svg|300x45px]]'''[[United Nations General Assembly]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1945'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- |The 1950 General Assembly resolution number 377 recognizes the right of the General Assembly, when the veto of a permanent member causes the Security Council to fail in maintaining the peace, to recommend the use of all actions including military force to preserve the peace. Paragraph 7 further recommends that member states maintain armed forces ready to be made available to serve as UN units up the recommendation of the Security Council or General Assembly. Used in Suez Crisis, 1956, Soviet Intervention in Hungary, 1956, the Lebanon-Jordan crisis, 1958, etc.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =United Nations General Assembly Resolution 377 | work = A/RES/377 Paragraphs 1 and 7 | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.derechos.org/human-rights/irak/doc/377uneng.html | doi = | accessdate = 2006-12-04 }}</ref> |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |}
{| class="wikitable" |- | style="background:lightblue" align="left" width="650px" | '''[[World Trade Organization]]''' | style="background:lightblue" align="center" width="120px" | ''Founded 1994'' |- | style="background:lightgrey" | '''Aspect''' | style="background:lightgrey" align="center" width="120px" | '''Supranational Element''' |- | The WTO Council can, with the votes of a three-fourths majority of member states, adopt an interpretation of trade agreements falling under WTO jurisdiction. | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |WTO Dispute Resolution Panels have compulsory jurisdiction, in that any state may bring an alleged violation of WTO trade law by another state to a panel for adjuciation. | align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |Decisions of dispute resolution panels are binding on state parties. |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |- |WTO Panel decisions may be enforced through authorization for slighted parties to undertake retaliatory trade sanctions. |align="center" width="120px" | 2 |}
